@pgleeson - The unique id / label is arbitrary and depends on what you want to do.

There can be several cell rules that apply to the same cell. That way for example you can create a rule that applies to all 'cellType':'IT' (if you have a unique 'cellModel' in the net), or 2 different rules that apply to {'cellType':'IT', 'cellModel':'HH'} and {'cellType':'IT', 'cellModel':'Izhi'}.

Also, you might want to apply certain properties only to a subset of cells, eg. after creating the standard cell rules, you could modify the morphology or biophysics only of cells within a certain cortical depth: 'conds': {'y': [400, 600]} 

Cell rules are applied additively, such that later rules modify existing values or add elements if these are missing.

I've worked around the issue by using a regular `graphene.Field`, `id` plus other arguments, and doing some trickery in the resolve method.

```python
class GraphQuery(graphene.ObjectType):
    topic = graphene.Field(Topic, id=graphene.String(), slug=graphene.String())

    def resolve_topic(self, args, info):
        field = relay.NodeField(Topic)
        if args.get('id'):
            return field.id_fetcher(args.['id'], info)
        return get_topic(info, **args)
```

@chshu first let me thank you for working on this, having flexible `TimerMilli` and `TimerMicro` will be super helpful. 

I have an idea for how to reuse the code for both types of timers. The key point as you mentioned is that the two types use different `Alarm` related APIs. What if we provide a pointer to the `Alarm` functions as an input parameter for methods in a common base class (virtual function trick without being virtual).

For example, we can define an `AlarmApi` struct like this:

````
struct AlarmApi
{
    void (*AlarmStartAt)(otInstance *aInstance, uint32_t aT0, uint32_t aDt);
    void (*AlarmStop)(otInstance *aInstance);
    uint32_t (*AlarmGetNow)(void);
};
````
Then defining a base Timer class like this (I removed all comments)

````
class TimerBase: public Ip6Locator, public Context
{
public:

    typedef void (*Handler)(Timer &aTimer);

    Timer(TimerScheduler &aScheduler, Handler aHandler, void *aContext):
        TimerSchedulerLocator(aScheduler),
        Context(aContext),
        mHandler(aHandler),
        mFireTime(0),
        mNext(this) {
    }

    uint32_t GetFireTime(void) const { return mFireTime; }

    bool IsRunning(void) const { return (mNext != this); }

    // `Start()`, `StartAt()`, `Stop()`, and `GetNow()` will be defined by sub-classes.

private:
    // The code for this can be shared, only change we may need is 
    // to pass the aNow as an input parameter (to avoid the need 
    // for having `GetNow()` method)
    bool DoesFireBefore(const Timer &aTimer, uint32_t aNow);

    void Fired(void) { mHandler(*this); }

    Handler         mHandler;
    uint32_t        mFireTime;
    Timer          *mNext;
};

class TimerMilli : public TimerBase
{
public:
    enum
    {
        kMaxDt = (1UL << 31) - 1,  //< Maximum permitted value for parameter `aDt` in `Start` and `StartAt` method.
    };

    // Here we define `Start` and `StartAt` and `Stop` 
    // and `GetNow` for the timer type using its 
    // corresponding scheduler.
}

// And same way for `TimerMicor` class.

````

We then have a `TimerSchedulerBase` which contains all the common code.

````
class TimerSchedulerBase: public Ip6Locator
{
    TimerSchedulerBase(void);

    void Add(TimerBase &aTimer, const AlarmApi &aAlarmApi);
    void Remove(TimerBase &aTimer, const AlarmApi &aAlarmApi);
    void ProcessTimer(const AlarmApi  &aAlarmApi);
private:
    void SetAlarm(const AlarmApi &aAlarmApi);
    static bool IsStrictlyBefore(uint32_t aTimeA, uint32_t aTimeB);

    TimerBase *mHead;
};
````

The common code use the input parameter `aAlarmApi` function pointers.

Then the two sub-classes for milli and micor scheduler will contain inline calls into base class providing the alarm API:

````
class TimerSchedulerMilli : public TimerSchedulerBase
{
public:
    TimerShceduelr(...)

    void Add(TimerMilli &aTimer)     { TimerSchedulerBase::Add(aTimer, sMilliAlarmApi); }
    void Remove(TimerMilli &aTimer)  { TimerSchedulerBase::Remove(aTimer, sMilliAlarmApi); }
    void ProcessTimer(void)  { TimerSchedulerBase::Process(aTimer, sMilliAlarmApi); }
    // ...

private:
    static const AlarmApi sMilliAlarmApi;
};

// In cpp file we define the `MilliAlarmApi` struct as a constant:

static const TimerSchedulerMilli::sMilliAlarmApi = { &otPlatAlarmStartAt, &otAlarmStop, &otAlarmgetNow };
````

And same way for the Micro one.
One thing I realized that we may need to make the `TimerScheduelrBase` be a `Ip6Locator` itself. For single-instance case this should not add any new variable and make the code simpler.

Thoughts?

